{{FHSST_Physics/Newtonian Gravitation}}
= Properties =
Gravitational attraction is a force and therefore must be described by a vector - so remember magnitude and direction. The force due to gravity acts between ''any'' two objects with mass. To determine the magnitude of the force we use the following equation:
{| |- |<math>\begin{matrix}F = \frac{G m_1 m_2}{r^2}\end{matrix}</math> | class="eqno" align="RIGHT" | (9.1) |}
This equation describes the force between two bodies, one of mass ''m''<sub>1</sub>, the other of mass ''m''<sub>2</sub> (both have units of kilograms, or kg for short). The ''G'' is Newton's`Gravitational Constant' (6.673&times;10<sup>&minus;11</sup> N&middot;m<sup>2</sup>&middot;kg<sup>-2</sup>) and ''r'' is the straight line distance between the two bodies in meters.
This means the bigger the masses, the greater the force between them. Simply put, big things matter big with gravity. The 1/''r''<sup>2</sup> factor (or you may prefer to say ''r''<sup>-2</sup>) tells us that the distance between the two bodies plays a role as well. The closer two bodies are, the stronger the gravitational force between them is. We feel the gravitational attraction of the Earth most at the surface since that is the closest we can get to it, but if we were in outer-space, we would barely even know the Earth's gravity existed!
Remember that
{| |- |<math>\begin{matrix}F=ma\end{matrix}</math> | class="eqno" align="RIGHT" | (9.2) |}
which means that every object on the earth feels the same gravitational acceleration! That means whether you drop a pen or a book (from the same height), they will both take the same length of time to hit the ground... in fact they will be head to head for the entire fall if you drop them at the same time. We can show this easily by using the two equations above (9.1 and 9.2). The force between the Earth (which has the mass ''m''<sub>e</sub>) and an object of mass ''m''<sub>o</sub> is
{| |- |<math>\begin{matrix}F=\frac{G m_o m_e}{r^2}\end{matrix}</math> | class="eqno" align="RIGHT" | (9.3) |}
and the acceleration of an object of mass ''m''<sub>o</sub> (in terms of the force acting on it) is
{| |- |<math>\begin{matrix}a_o=\frac{F}{m_o}\end{matrix}</math> | class="eqno" align="RIGHT" | (9.4) |}
So we substitute equation (9.3) into equation (9.4), and we find that
{| |- |<math>\begin{matrix}a_o=\frac{G m_e}{r^2}\end{matrix}</math> | class="eqno" align="RIGHT" | (9.5) |}
Since it doesn't matter what ''m''<sub>o</sub> is, this tells us that the acceleration on a body (due to the Earth's gravity) does not depend on the mass of the body. Thus all objects feel the same gravitational acceleration. The force on different bodies will be different but the acceleration will be the same. Due to the fact that this acceleration caused by gravity is the same on all objects we label it differently, instead of using ''a'' we use ''g'' which we call the gravitational acceleration.

{{FHSST_Physics/Newtonian Gravitation}}
= Mass and Weight =
Weight is a force which is measured in Newtons, it is the force on an object due to gravity. People are always asking other people "What is your weight?" when a physicist might ask the same question as "What is your mass?".
Mass is measured in kilograms (kg) and is the amount of matter in an object, it doesn't change unless you add or remove matter from the object (if you continue to study physics through to university level, you will find that Einstein's theory of relativity means that mass can change when you travel as fast as light does, but you don't need to worry about that right now). There are 1000 g in 1 kg and 1000 kg in a tonne.
To change mass into weight we use Newton's 2nd Law which is <math>F = ma</math>. The weight is the force and gravity the acceleration, it can be rewritten as:
{| |- |<math>\begin{matrix}W=mg\end{matrix}</math> | class="eqno" align="RIGHT" | (9.2) |}
''W'' is the weight, measured in newtons. ''m'' is the mass, measured in kilograms and ''g'' is the acceleration due to gravity, measured in metres per second squared; it is equal to about 10 on the Earth. The exact value of Earths equatorial surface gravity is 9.7801 <math>m.s^{-2}</math>.
== Examples == 1. A bag of sugar has a mass of 1 kg, what is it's weight? (Acceleration due to gravity = 10 <math>m.s^{-2}</math>)
Step 1: Always write out the equation, it helps you to understand the question, and you will get marks as well. {| |- |<math>\begin{matrix}W=mg\end{matrix}</math> |- | class="eqno" align="RIGHT" |(9.7) |}
Step 2: Fill in all the values you know. (remember to make sure the mass is in kilograms and NOT in grams or tonnes!)
{| |- |<math>\begin{matrix}W = 1 \times 10\end{matrix}</math> |- |<math>W = 10</math> |- | class="eqno" align="RIGHT" |(9.8) |}
Step 3: Write out the answer remembering to include the units! You will lose marks if you don't
{| |- |<math>\begin{matrix}W = 10 \ newtons\end{matrix}</math> |- | class="eqno" align="RIGHT" |(9.9) |}
2. A space-man has a mass of 90 kg, what is his weight (a) on the earth? (b) on the moon? (c) in outer space? (The acceleration due to gravity on the earth is 10 <math>m.s^{-2}</math>, on the moon gravity is about 1/6 of the gravity on earth).
1: {| |- |<math>\begin{matrix}W=mg\end{matrix}</math> |- |- |<math>\begin{matrix}W = 90 \times 10 = 900\end{matrix}</math> |- |<math>W = 900 \ newtons</math> |- | class="eqno" align="RIGHT" |(9.10) |}
2:
{| |- |<math>W = M \ g</math> |- |- |<math>\begin{matrix}W = 90 \times \ 10 \times \frac{1}{6} = 150 \end{matrix} </math> |- |<math>W = 150 \ newtons</math> |- | class="eqno" align="RIGHT" |(9.10) |}
3: Weightless in outer space because ''g'' = 0.
So now when somebody asks you your weight, you know to reply ``Anything!! But my mass is a different matter!"

{{FHSST_Physics/Newtonian Gravitation}}
= Comparative problems =
Here always work with multiplicative factors to find something new in terms of something old.
==Worked Example 57 Comparative Problem 1== '''Question:''' On Earth a man weighs 700 N. Now if the same man was instantaneously beamed to the planet Zirgon, which has the same size as the Earth but twice the mass, what would he weigh?
'''Answer:'''
Step 1 :
We start with the situation on earth:
{| |- |<math>\begin{matrix}W = mg = G\frac{m_Em}{r^2}\end{matrix}</math> |- | class="eqno" align="RIGHT" | (9.13) |}
Step 2 :
Now we consider the provje
{| |- |<math>\begin{matrix}W_Z= mg_Z = G\frac{m_Zm}{r_Z^2}\end{matrix}</math> |- | class="eqno" align="RIGHT" | (9.14) |}
but we know that <math>m_Z = 2m_E</math> and we know that ''r''<sub>Z</sub> = ''r'' so we could write the equation again and substitute these relationships in:
Step 3 :
{| |- |<math>\begin{matrix}W_Z= mg_Z = G\frac{(m_Z)m}{(r_Z)^2}\end{matrix}</math> |- | class="eqno" align="RIGHT" | (9.15) |}
Step 4 :
{| |- |<math>\begin{matrix}W_Z= mg_Z = G\frac{(2m_E)m}{(r)^2}\end{matrix}</math> |- | class="eqno" align="RIGHT" | (9.16) |}
{| |- |<math>\begin{matrix}W_Z= 2( G\frac{(m_E)m}{(r)^2})\end{matrix}</math> |- | class="eqno" align="RIGHT" | (9.17) |}
Step 5 :
{| |- |<math>\begin{matrix}W_Z= 2(W)\end{matrix}</math> |- | class="eqno" align="RIGHT" | (9.18) |}
so on Zirgon he weighs 1400 N.
== Principles ==
* Write out first case * Write out all relationships between variable from first and second case * Write out second case * Substitute all first case variables into second case * Write second case in terms of first case
<hr style="background-color:red" />
{| |- | [[Image:fhsst_magnify.png|110px]] |The acceleration due to gravity at the Earth's surface is, by convention, equal to 9.80665 ''ms''<sup>-2</sup>. (The actual value varies slightly over the surface of the Earth). This quantity is known as ''g''. The following is a list of the gravitational accelerations (in multiples of ''g'') at the surfaces of each of the planets in our solar system:
{| cellpadding="3" |- | align="CENTER" | Mercury | align="CENTER" | 0.376 |- | align="CENTER" | Venus | align="CENTER" | 0.903 |- | align="CENTER" | Earth | align="CENTER" | 1 |- | align="CENTER" | Mars | align="CENTER" | 0.38 |- | align="CENTER" | Jupiter | align="CENTER" | 2.34 |- | align="CENTER" | Saturn | align="CENTER" | 1.16 |- | align="CENTER" | Uranus | align="CENTER" | 1.15 |- | align="CENTER" | Neptune | align="CENTER" | 1.19 |- | align="CENTER" | Pluto | align="CENTER" | 0.066 |}
Note:
The "surface" is taken to mean the cloud tops of the gas giants (Jupiter, Saturn, Uranus and Neptune) in the above table. |}
==Worked Example 58 Comparative Problem 2== '''Question:''' On Earth a man weighs 70 kg. On the planet Beeble how much will he weigh if Beeble has mass half of that of the Earth and a radius one quarter that of the earth.
'''Answer:'''
Step 1 :
We start with the situation on earth:
{| |- |<math>\begin{matrix}W = mg = G\frac{m_Em}{r^2}\end{matrix}</math> |- | class="eqno" align="RIGHT" | (9.19) |}
Step 2 :
Now we consider the provje
{| |- |<math>\begin{matrix}W_B= mg_B = G\frac{m_Bm}{r_B^2}\end{matrix}</math> |- | class="eqno" align="RIGHT" | (9.20) |}
but we know that <math>m_Z = \frac{1}{2}m_E</math> and we know that <math>r_Z = \frac{1}{4}r</math> so we could write the equation again and substitute these relationships in:
Step 3 :
{| |- |<math>\begin{matrix}W_Z= mg_Z = G\frac{(m_Z)m}{(r_Z)^2}\end{matrix}</math> |- | class="eqno" align="RIGHT" | (9.21) |}
Step 4 :
{| |- |<math>\begin{matrix}W_Z= mg_Z = G\frac{(\frac{1}{2}m_E)m}{(\frac{1}{4}r)^2}\end{matrix}</math> |- | class="eqno" align="RIGHT" | (9.22) |}
{| |- |<math>\begin{matrix}W_Z= 8( G\frac{(m_E)m}{(r)^2})\end{matrix}</math> |- | class="eqno" align="RIGHT" | (9.23) |}
Step 5 :
<math>\begin{matrix}W_Z= 8(W)\end{matrix}</math>
But although the man exerts 8 times as much force due to gravity, he still weighs 70 kg on Beeble!
